            "creation_date": 1436654186,
            "body": "<p>I will use CSS class. First set styleSheet for javaFX app:\n(<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/user-interface-tutorial/apply-css.htm#CHDGHCDG\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/user-interface-tutorial/apply-css.htm#CHDGHCDG<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<p>Then add class to styleSheet:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>.imageButton {\n    -fx-graphic: url(\"@../icons/document_32.png\");\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Add style class to button and button have image.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>// Create button\nButton btn = new Button(\"New Document\");\n\n// This command add style to button...\nbtn.getStyleClass().add(\"imageButton\");\n\n// Remove style and image\nbtn.getStyleClass().remove(\"imageButton\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 31362520,
            "question_id": 31358812
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2df48e3dceeda6c6022ff3bea6ced024?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 5214743,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4170073,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4170073/aw-think",
                "reputation": 4803,
                "display_name": "aw-think"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1436712131,
            "creation_date": 1436712131,
            "body": "<p>This is a bad solution, but I can't understand why you need it. It's much simpler to set the graphic directly with the image you already have.<\/p>\n\n<p>But here it is, it assumes that you have an Icon file called ok.png in your package where the class is, like the picture below.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/i2inU.png\" alt=\"Structure\"><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import javafx.application.Application;\nimport javafx.geometry.Pos;\nimport javafx.scene.Node;\nimport javafx.scene.Scene;\nimport javafx.scene.control.Button;\nimport javafx.scene.image.Image;\nimport javafx.scene.image.ImageView;\nimport javafx.scene.layout.VBox;\nimport javafx.stage.Stage;\n\n\npublic class JavaFXApplication1 extends Application {\n\n    @Override\n    public void start(Stage primaryStage) {\n        // create an image, an image is not a Node!\n        Image imageOk = new Image(getClass().getResourceAsStream(\"ok.png\"));\n        // create a new Button\n        Button sourceBtn = new Button(\"Ok\", new ImageView(imageOk));\n        // get the buttons graphic\n        Node node = sourceBtn.getGraphic();\n        // you have to cast the node to an ImageView\n        ImageView imageView = (ImageView) node;\n        // from the ImageView you are able to get the Image\n        Image imageCopy = imageView.getImage();\n        // a new Button instance\n        Button destBtn = new Button(\"I'am OK, too\");\n\n        // now set the new graphic the same as the other button\n        sourceBtn.setOnAction((action) -&gt; {\n            destBtn.setGraphic(new ImageView(imageCopy));\n        });\n\n        VBox root = new VBox(10.0);\n        root.setAlignment(Pos.CENTER);\n        root.getChildren().addAll(sourceBtn, destBtn);\n\n        Scene scene = new Scene(root, 350, 300);\n\n        primaryStage.setTitle(\"Hello World!\");\n        primaryStage.setScene(scene);\n        primaryStage.show();\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * @param args the command line arguments\n     */\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        launch(args);\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The application will look like this initial<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/MdO2y.png\" alt=\"Initial\"><\/p>\n\n<p>and after clicked the image button:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/wlg7H.png\" alt=\"After\"><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 31368992,
            "question_id": 31358812
        }
